Exploring Yelp Reviews¶

In this assignment, I'll explore restaurant review data available through the Yelp Dataset Challenge. The dataset includes Yelp data for user reviews and business information for 10 metropolitan areas. Cleveland were chosen since the data is not too large — the data for the other cities can be downloaded from the Yelp download page.

Part 1: testing how well sentiment analysis works.¶

Because Yelp reviews include the number of stars given by the user, the Yelp data set provides a unique opportunity to test how well the sentiment analysis works by comparing the number of stars to the polarity of reviews.

Part 2: analyzing correlations between restaurant reviews and census data¶

I'll explore geographic trends in the restaurant reviews, comparing our sentiment analysis results with user stars geographically. We'll also overlay review stars on maps of household income (using census data).

Background readings¶

  • Does sentiment analysis work?
  • The Geography of Taste: Using Yelp to Study Urban Culture

1.3 Review stop words¶

nltk library is used to remove any stop words from the list of words in each review.

Overwrites the 'formatted_text' column to contain a list of lower-cased words in each review, with no stop words.

In [6]:
import nltk
import re

# load stop words
nltk.download('stopwords')
stop_words = list(set(nltk.corpus.stopwords.words('english')))

[nltk_data] Downloading package stopwords to /Users/zh3n/nltk_data...
[nltk_data]   Package stopwords is already up-to-date!
In [7]:
def remove_punctuation(word):
    # using re to remove the punctuation
    # instead of the string package to deal with
    # words like "example." or "(another" and make them
    # "example" or "another"
    return re.sub(r"[^\w]","",word)

def remove_stop_words_and_punctuation(word_list):
    # remove stop words and punctuations in the word list
    word_list_return = []
    for word in word_list:
        word_remove = remove_punctuation(word)
        # if word is null, pass this
        if not word_remove: continue
        if word_remove not in stop_words:
            word_list_return.append(word_remove)
    return word_list_return
In [8]:
# apply the func
review_data.formatted_text = review_data.formatted_text.apply(remove_stop_words_and_punctuation)

What do the charts indicate for the effectiveness of our sentiment analysis?

  1. In short, the charts indicate that sentiment analysis of reviews works pretty good.

  2. The polarity of reviews and the stars have a positive relationship, so reviews with more stars tend to have a greater polarity value. And it can be a good predictor of stars.

  3. The subjectivity of reviews and stars don't have such strong relationship, but according to the figure, more stars of a review usually means more subjectivity.

  4. There are a lot of outliers in both figures, indecates the possibility that some emotions are not being interpreted effectively from the words.

1.6.2 Re-format the data¶

In [16]:
def reshape_data(review_subset):
    """
    Reshape the input dataframe of review data.
    """
    from pandas import Series, merge
    
    X = (review_subset['formatted_text']
         .apply(Series)
         .stack()
         .reset_index(level=1, drop=True)
         .to_frame('word'))
    
    
    R = review_subset[['polarity', 'stars', 'review_id']]
    
    return merge(R, X, left_index=True, right_index=True).reset_index(drop=True)
